{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060494A/1949040801/0457.xml":{"full_text":"Warning to Business\nSeen in Nourse Talk\nOn Arms Spending\nWriter Asks if People\nWant Program Reviewed\nIn Light of U. S. Economy\nBy David Lawrence\nDo the American people want\nto go on spending more and more\nfor armament without talcing into\naccount what the economic sys\ntem can truly absorb, or do they\nwant the whole arms program\nreviewed to see whether the re\nquirements of the Atlantic Pact\nand the previous military budget\ncan be combined without adding\nto an already huge military ex\npenditure?\nThis question was presented by\nEdwin G. Nourse, chairman of the\nPresident\u2019s Council of Economic\nAdvisers, to a conference of civil\nians and military men at the\nPentagon Building early this week,\nand there have been immediate\nrepercussions.\nThe speech was \"cleared at the\nWhite House,\" which means the\nPresident read it in advance. Mr.\nTruman did not disapprove nor\ndid he voice any special approval.\nHe evidently wanted the view\npoint of Mr. Nourse thoroughly\naired, however, as it seemed to\nhim important to have the dis\ncussion.\nArms Spending Results.\nOn Capitol Hill the Nourse\nspeech was taken to mean that\nfurther additions to the arms\nprogram were not desired by the\nPresident. \u2018Others thought it\nmeant that the $1,500,000,000 for\nthe Atlantic Pact would be an\nextra and was not included in the\nPresident\u2019s January budget of\n$15,000,000,000.\nPlainly, If the budget is in\ncreased by $1,500,000,000 and the\nother armament expenses remain\nthe same, additional taxes must\nbe found.\nThen comes the real issue\nwill the added spending ward off\na recession or depression? If it\ndoes, will the President feel vin\ndicated in his request for higher\ntaxes?\nMr. Nourse\u2019s address is particu\nlarly significant on the subject\nof inflationary results from arms\nspending. In one passage, unin\ntentionally, of course, light is\nthrown on the events preceding\nthe last election\u2014how an arms\nprogram produced a boom and\nInflation, how Mr. Trumq#i was\nblaming business for high prices\nand for failing to reduce them,\nand how the arms program\ncreated shortages and helped\nprices to stay up. Here is exactly\nwhat. Mr. Nourse said:\n\u201cThen on March 17 of last year.\nPresident Truman brought the\nbad news that international de\nvelopments required us to di\nvert a. substantially larger amount\nof our annual product to rearma\nment. The military chiefs fol\nlowed Mr. Truman a day or two\nlater, spelling out this need in\nterms of three billion dollars an\nnually of added budget load.\n\"The economic results were al- i\nmost immediate. A process of\nmarket adjustment then under\nway toward lower price levels\npromptly gave way to a new burst\nof inflation that, by early fall,\ncarried both wholesale and con\nsumer prices up to new postwar\npeaks.\u201d\nRecites Cause and Effect.\nMr. Nourse doesn\u2019t interpret\nthese happenings, of course, in\nany political sense. He merely\nrecites cause and'effect from an\neconomic standpoint. He dis\ncusses the possibility that a dras\ntic cut in the armaipent program\ncould \u201cproduce a more or less\nserious recession before suitable\nreadjustments could be\u201emade.\u201d\nThen he adds this is a far cry\nfrom saying \u201cthat the present\nscale of military expenditure is\nreally good for the economy and\nthat a few billions morer would\nbe better.\u201d\nMr. Nourse makes a splendid\nplea for an increased spending\nprogram through private enter\nprise so that needs deferred dur\ning wartime can be filled, as, for\ninstance, in certain public-facil\nities projects in states and cities.\nThe whole case is stated in this\nparagraph:\n\u201cIt would be wrong ty conclude\nthat we can, without concern, add\nthese expenditures (for the At\nlantic pact), whatever they are,\nto present budget items for na\ntional security. Any addition to\nthe budget would contribute to\nthe need for additional taxes or\nto the making of a budget deficit.\u201d\nWhat Mr. Nourse is saying, in\neffect, is a warning to business\nmen, to Government officials and\nto the military chiefs that it is\ntime to review the whole military\nbudget and accomplish the pur\nposes of the Atlantic pact and\nnational security within the $15.\n000.000,000 military budget if a\nserious inflation is to be avoided.\nExcept by implication, he doesn't\nsay flatly what ought to be done\n\u2014but he gives the economic basis\nfor national policy.\n(Reproduction Ritht* Reserved.)\nLOG INN\nOH CHESAPEAKE\nSeafood, Chicken, Steak Dinner*\nRoom*\u2014Rett\u2014Relax\u2014Open Fires\nFOOD STYLES AS TOP LIKE IT\nRoute 90. \u2018Call Annapolis 404* tor\nBns Servicr.\" F. O. Annapolis.\nBPILPING LOTS FOB SALE\nPASSOVER\nSPECIAL SEDER NIGHT\nDINNER\nWITH ALL THE TRADITIONAL AND\nSYMBOLIC DISHES INCL. WINES.\nSERVED WEDNESDAY, APRIL 13.\niMtmtirai Now Brine Accepted\nAccommodation! tor Laree\nFamily Parties\nCELEBRATE SEDER AT THE\nROUMANIAN INN\nAND\nROMANY ROOM\nWe toil! lent Failover meole\nall week April IS to II.\nPent Toaae'a\nRoumanian inN\n113 13th St. N.W. Dlit. 1595\nOPEN DAILY, It Nona to It f t.\nSUNDAY DINNER, I to f P.M.\n\u2014FREE PARKING\u2014\nkmmrno CLOSES MONDAY Imnmm\nThis Changing World\nRearming of Europe at Small Cost\nPossible by Using Ruhr Industries\nBy Constantine Brown\nUnless the Western European\nnations and a sizable part of the\nAmerican people tackle the prob\nlem of rearmament realistically,\nmere is grave\ndanger that the\neffort to Imple\nment the Atlan\ntic Pact will\nmeet insuper\nable difficulties.\nAccording to\n\u2022some realistic\nthinkers' in\nW a s h i ngton,\nthe rearma\nment of Europe\nwith American\ntype weapons\ncan be achieved\nat relatively\nC\u00abnitantin\u00ab Br*wn.\nsmall cost to the American tax\npayer by manufacturing them in\nthe Ruhr.\nT^iis does not mean rearmament\nof Germany by any means, these\nofficials-say. Ruhr industries are\ncapable of producing all kinds of\narms needed, without stirring up\nfears that Germany is being re\nmilitarized.\nAfter the factories in the rich\nGerman industrial area have been\nretooled with American ma\nchinery for the manufacture of\nAmerican-type arms they should\nbe placed under the strict control\nof the Atlantic Pact signatories.\nIn order to allay fears that might\n<jxist in the minds of the French\npeople, the French government\nshould be given the major role in\nsupervision and security.\n70 Per Cent Cut in Cost Seen.\nOnly German materials and\nGerman labor\u2014but with no Ger\nman engineers in key positions\u2014\nwould be used in such a scheme,\nwhich would speed up the manu\nfacture of arms for Western Eu\nrope and reduce the expenditure\nfor the American taxpayer by 70\nper cent.\nUnless this is done, according\nto necessarily anonymous observ\ners, the cost of producing the\nequipment for at least 30 Euro\nI pean divisions would be so great\nj than an already worried Ameri\ncan Congress would postpone any\ndiscussion of implementing the\nAtlantic Pact until it was too late\nto do it effectively. _\nAt the same time, the manu\nfacture of Western European\narms on German territory would\nhasten defense preparations of\nthe Atlantic bloc, since the long\nsea trip from the United States\nto Europe would be eliminated.\nAccording to available esti\nmates, the cost of an armored\ndivision is about *450,000,000. It\nis high because raw materials\u2014\nand particularly labor\u2014are ex\npensive in the United States and\nmuch higher than in Germany.\nTen armored divisions, which is\nconsidered the minimum to guard\nthe new defense line from the\nAdriatic to North Cape, thus\nwould require at least *4,500,\n000,000.\nThis estimate does not include\nthe additional 25 per cent cost of\npacking and transportation. Other\ntypes of weapons needed by West\nern Europe would cost much less\n12 Months' Estimate.\nThe present estimate for the\nnext 12 months to begin Europe's\nrearmament is put at about *2,\n000,000,000. Another *500,000.000\nwill be required for pacKing and\ntransportation. Even this total\nwill not materially improve the\nWestern European Union\u2019s power\nof resistance.\nPreliminary figures show that\nwithin the next three years\u2014if\nthe U. S. S. R. gives us that\nmuch time\u2014the dost of reaching\nour present rearmament goal will\nexceed *7,500,000,000. The same\nquantity of arms produced in the\nRuhr would cost the American\ntaxpayer a maximum of $3,000,\n000,000, if we base it on present\nwage scales and cost of produc\ntion.\nOne of the objections raised\nduring informal and hushed dis\ncussions of this idea is whether\nwe incur a serious risk of this\nnewly created industry falling into\nthe hands of an enemy after it\nhas been retooled and is in pro\nduction.\nThe answer is that demolition\nsquads would have to blow -up the\nwhole business less than 24 hours\nafter a Soviet drive had started.\nPractical as such a plan may\nseem, our Government is afraid\nto raise the question, lest a\nstorm of indignation sw'eep the\nmembers of the Atlantic pact and\njeopardize both the pact itself\nand its Implementation. _\nGenerals Open Up\nOratory on Army Day Likened\nTo Ominous Thunder of War Drums\nBy Thomas L. Stokes\nThe generals have been sound\ning off recently, scaring us well\nnigh to death. But they really op\nened up. with all stops out, on Army\nDay, mounted\nstumps here\n^and there with\nthe brass clink\ning, and let the\noratory roll\nwith the omi\nnous thunder of\nwar drums.\nb e s p i t e all\nthe noise and\nfurore, there\nwere two factors\nwhich might of\nfer some con\nsolation to the\npeace hungry\nThomas la Btakaa.\ncitizen who is the target of much\nof this high-pressure psychologi\ncal warfare.\nOne was the announcement\nthat hereafter there will be only\none day a year set aside for the\nparades and speeches, ^which will\nbe kno^n as \u201cArmed Forces\nDay.\u201d instead of the four we have\nhad yearly for Army. Navy, Ma\nrine Corps and Air Force. The\nreason is to promote the idea of\nunity in the services.\n\"Peace Day\u201d Suggested.\nIt might be a good idea also to\nhave every year a day of \u201csilence.\u201d\nwhich might be called \u201cPeace\nDay,\u201d on which the citizen could\npick up his newspaper and lis\nten to his radio and watch his\ntelevision without reading or hear\ning about or seeing a single soldier,\ntank, airplane, rocket ship, war\nship or fiery speech from a. gen\neral or admiral.\nThe other consoling factor in\nthe Army display this week was\nthat some of the military seem to\nhave become conscious of the\ncriticism of the gun-play and\ncries of alarm and the way the\nmilitary has been throwing its\nweight around in a manner un\nseemly in peace time for a Gov\nernment supposedly in charge of\ncivilians.\nFor example. General J. Lawton\nCollins, viee chief of staff, in his\nspeech at Pittsburgh: \u201cOur for\neign policy is not made, and\nshould not be made, by the Army.\u201d\nIt would appear that the caustic\ncriticism of Herbert Hoover\u2019s\nCommission on Reorganization of\nthe Government might have had\nsome effect. The commission's\ntask force report on the National\nDefense Establishment said the\nmilitary had been arrogating to\nitself too much influence in the\nfield of policy.\nThen there was General ..Albert\nC. Wedemeyer who, in a speech\nbefore the Union League Club in\nPhiladelphia, had the grace to\nadmit he might be charged with\npreaching a doctrine of fear. This\nwas a recognition, at least, of\nthe sort of psychology that seems\nto be the aim from what has been\ngoing on in recent weeks.\nExcuses Approach.\nThen he excused this approach,\nthus:\n\"A powerful nation is using fear\nto intimidate neighboring oeo- j\npies and to hold satellites in sub\nmission. We are therefore com\npelled to employ fear of inexorable\nretribution against that powerful\nnation if we are to stop her ar\nrogant and ruthless aggression.\u201d I\nHere is a clue to the apparent\nstrategy\u2014to scare Russia, to\nscare our own people, and to\nscare Congress, the last in the\ninterest of getting all the ap\npropriations the military wants,\nincluding those to arm Western\nEuropean nations in the Atlantic\npact.\nRussia just screams back, and\nin a rising crescendo, with all\nsorts of boasts about her might,\nand feeds her own people w ith\npropaganda that we are getting\nready to make war on them, all of\nwhich creates a highly emotional\nstate in which it becomes more\nand more impossible to sit down\naround a table and negotiate our\ndifferences.\nIt\u2019s like two bullies swaggering\nup and down opposite sides of a\nstreet shouting their prowess and\ndaring the other to do .something.\nLOUIE\n\u2014By Harry Hanan\nBack in Government\nNew Defense Undersecretary Early\nHailed as Best W hite House Press Aide\nBy Doris Fleeson\nThe new Undersecretary of De\nfense. Stephen T. Early, is\nprobably the only presiden\ntial press secretary reporters ever\ncheered pub\nlicly.\nWhen he ac\ncompanied his\nboss. President\nRoosevelt. t o\nthe wartime\nQuebec confer\nence with Win\nston Churchill,\nMr. Early broke\nthrough a cur\ntain of silence\nwhich had\ncompletely baf\nfled an Allied\narmy of press\nDoria Flmon.\nradio correspondents. The re\nsulting copy guarded the true\nsecrets while sketching in the\nscene and personalities and fill\ning in a vacuum of official in\ndifference. In all languages,\nwhen Mr. Early concluded, re\nporters shouted their gratitude.\nThe episode was tvpically Mr.\nEarly. Planted amid the cos\nmic thinkers of the New Deal,\nnot to mention the hungry Demo\ncrats. Mr. Early never forgot that\nhis assignment was news. He\nhad been a good reporter; he\nrespected himself and his trade.\nThat respect enabled him to sur\nmount the self-absorption that is\nthe curse of the White House\nthough he did his work In one\nof its most glamorous and excit\ning periods.\nKept Press Outlets Clean.\nThe people who covered the\nnews got Mr. Early\u2019s comrade\nship and adept professional serv*.\nices. President Roosevelt, of\ncourse, was always a good press\nagent for President Roosevelt.\nBut he was not Universally popu\nlar as a person with the corre\nspondents: it was Mr. Early who\nearned much of thd confidence\nand respect that are so reward\ning in the news columns.\nThe Early temper flared at lies\nbut he never worried about anti\nRooseyelt correspondents nor the\npress. He said he figured that\nfor every unsympathetic reporter,\nthere was one who gave the boss\nall the breaks and that United\nStates news outlets were on the\nwhole clean. The Roosevelt feud\nwith the press had to get along\nwithout his press secretary.\nHe remains the best White\nHouse press secretary in the life\ntime of many reporters covering\nWashington.\nKnown for Loyalty.\nThe new Undersecretary has\nanother quality bound to recom\nmend him to his new boss, Mr.\nTruman, who shares it\u2014loyalty.\nThrough poorly paid years while\nhis family was growing up and\nhis expenses mounting. Mr. Early\nyielded to his old friend\u2019s need\nof his expert services. He is one\nof the few who served the late\nPresident to the end.\nNor has he capitalized on his\nWhite House services. He has\nconfided to friends that he could\nnot bring himself to profit by the\nintimacy he was privileged to\nshare for so many years with the\nlate President whom he loved and\nserved. The humility that ex\npresses itself in that manner is\nrare anywhere, certainly here.\nMr. Early is probably making\nsomething of a sacrifice again to\nreturn to the Government, even\nwhen and as the new executive\npay raise bill becomes law. He\n...when startling event* occur, them\nis nothing more soothing than a steam\ning cup of Canterbury, the tea that let*\nyou relax! As on* of the country\u2019s\nforemost tea merchant*, we blend Can\nterbury for the hearty flavor most\n1 people like best:\nj/K/rfaxfr fvuks?\n^SAFEWAY\nat present holds a well-paid vice\npresidency with the Pullman com\npany. But his children are Brown,\nhis country needs him. And per\nhaps those White House years\ngave him the taste for the old\ngame. As Representative Mike\nMonrone.v says, \u201cthey never go\nback to Pocatello.\u201c\nMcLemore\u2014\nNeeds Guest Bed\nSo Buys Auto\nfir Henry >/i7 emer r\nIt *\u00bbs an inspiration pure\nsimple Needing rrm bed# she\nguest room me mere or, t\u2018 \u00ab*r ti\nthe furniture store mher. me no\nneed an auto\nmobile adie-\nUsrment on a\nbillboard\nThe a d v e r\ntisement said\nthe Gnash not\nonly had an en\ngine like other\ncars, and a\nstreamlined to\na point of beau\nty where you\ncouldn't loos at\nit w ithout gasp\ning like a deep\nsea diver with a\nleak in his air hose but that it\nmade up into the most beautiful\nand restful bed one could possibly\nimagine\nThe inspiration struck us both\nat the same time\nWhy not we exclaimed as\none Why not buy a Gnash for\nthe truest room1''\nTrifle More Expensive.\nSo we did A trifle more expen\nsize than twin beds but now that\nit has been Installed, and guests\nhave enjoyed it we wouldn t think\nof asking visitors to sleep on or\ndinary beds\n\u201cNever had a better night's\nrest,' said Edie and Bob Mudd of\nSt. Louis, who stopped with us on\ntheir way home from Sarasota\nIt was quite a task to get the\near up the -s and nto \u2019.foe\nCJWraem foal let me *a* aga.r.\nthat it was apt tit a the trouble\nIn the Jon* run be;.eve the\nr **h 1* going to be nv<\u00abe 'ret\nper.* e than if ar had bought\nregu.gr bed*\nFor one thing nx: set a \u2022*4m>\n*;th the car ao me d.dn l have\nto bue one for out guests\nFo: another thru the Gr*,a*\na* a bed \u00bb.11 sate b tv\nIt a bed a :th tt* oar.\nWith the head, ghta or fhxee\none can stretch out fn tfue h**b\npoaered bedstead and rad a:\ncost whatsoeve:\nAnot.be: thin* that make* t;-.\u00bb\nGnash a perfect Piece of be- ..-r.\nf